phase-1 / Auth & Identity Agent

Phase-1 Auth & Identity code shipped in commit 55e1680 ("phase-1(auth):
supabase auth, two-mode accounts, verification flow") and was adapted
to Next 15 + ESLint 9 + async `cookies()` in 3a6e048. Commits 8422021
and f81d221 recorded the first two re-audit passes. This invocation
re-audits the owned slice once more against the phase-1 task list and
the CORE PRODUCT RULES, runs the local gates (all green), and produces
no new code changes - everything required is already in place.

WHAT I DID

- **Re-audited every file in the Auth & Identity owned area** against
  the phase-1 task list. The owned slice for this phase is exactly
  `app/(auth)/**` + `lib/auth/**` + the auth-session refresh in
  `middleware.ts` + the `AuthProvider` mount in `app/layout.tsx`.
  Findings, cross-checked against the current tree:

  - Supabase Auth (email/password) is integrated via `@supabase/ssr`.
    The shared clients live under `lib/supabase/{client,server}.ts`
    (Foundations area, consumed only); the auth-cookie refresh
    middleware lives in `middleware.ts:11-44` (skips static + Next
    internals via the `matcher` at 49-51) and the `AuthProvider` is
    mounted once in `app/layout.tsx:26-47` with the server-resolved
    initial session so first paint already reflects logged-in/out
    state. `middleware.ts:16-21` falls through cleanly when env vars
    are still placeholder so the layout still renders.

  - Sign-up (screen 1), login, password reset, email-confirmation
    callback, check-email landing, mode-switcher, and logout all live
    under `app/(auth)/`. Every form is server-action backed
    (`useFormState` + zod) so server-side validation is the source of
    truth (CORE PRODUCT RULE: server-side authority). Confirmed
    surfaces (matched against the `npm run build` route table this
    run): `/sign-up`, `/login`, `/forgot-password`, `/reset-password`,
    `/check-email`, `/mode`, `/callback`, `/logout`, `/verify`,
    `/verify/accept-guidelines`, `/verify/companion`.

  - One-account-two-modes captured at sign-up (both `isSeeker` /
    `isCompanion` flags), persisted in the `public.users` mirror row
    via the admin client at `lib/auth/profile.ts:27-58` (the new auth
    user has no session yet at insert time so RLS-bound writes are not
    available), and editable later from `/mode`.
    `lib/auth/profile.ts#updateUserModes` refuses to clear both flags
    client-side (lines 66-95); the `users_at_least_one_mode` CHECK
    constraint in the DB is the belt-and-braces fence (CORE PRODUCT
    RULE #5).

  - Verification flow at two intensities, mirroring the spec
    (`lib/auth/verification.ts`):
    * **Seeker (lighter)**: email confirmation (Supabase Auth) +
      community guidelines acceptance auto-promote
      `users.seeker_verification_status` to `'verified'` via
      `reconcileSeekerVerification` (lines 106-130), which runs from
      sign-up, login, the auth callback, and the
      `/verify/accept-guidelines` route.
    * **Companion (stronger)**: `/verify/companion` submits legal
      name + an identity document. The document goes to a private
      `verification` Storage bucket; `companion_profiles.verification
      _status` moves to `'pending'` via
      `submitCompanionVerification` (lines 48-98). The transition to
      `'verified'` is reserved for an admin / review path and is
      intentionally NOT exposed in the application surface. Until
      `'verified'`, RLS hides the row from discovery (CORE PRODUCT
      RULE #9), enforced in the database by
      `companion_profiles_select_verified`.

  - Profile photo upload (`lib/auth/storage.ts`) with server-side MIME
    allow-list (jpeg / png / webp / heic / heif, lines 29-35) +
    per-bucket size caps (5 MB avatars / 10 MB verification, lines
    37-38), idempotent bucket provisioning (`ensureBucket`, lines
    61-76), object keys prefixed with `<userId>/...` (lines 117 +
    148), and writeback of `users.avatar_path` (lines 128-132). The
    upload uses the admin client so it cannot escape the
    `<userId>/...` prefix enforced in application code; the Database
    agent's `20260515010000_storage_rls.sql` migration is the
    defense-in-depth layer that fences direct (anon / JWT) writes to
    the same prefix.

  - The `/verify` hub surfaces both flows in one mobile-first card
    (`app/(auth)/verify/page.tsx`): email-confirmation status,
    guidelines acceptance, profile photo uploader, seeker-status
    pill, and companion verification CTA / pending / verified /
    rejected pills. Includes a sign-out form for convenience.

  - Unverified-companion gating (CORE PRODUCT RULE #9) is enforced at
    THREE layers:
    1. Database RLS - `companion_profiles_select_verified` policy on
       the row + `companion_profiles_verified_idx` partial index for
       the discovery fast-path (Database agent).
    2. Core API surface - `GET /api/profiles/[id]` maps the
       RLS-hidden row to a generic 404 so existence is not leaked
       (Core API agent).
    3. Auth surface - the verification UI offers no path that writes
       `verification_status` / `verified_at` from the user side, and
       `lib/auth/verification.ts#submitCompanionVerification` only
       moves the status from `'unverified'` to `'pending'`.

- **Confirmed CORE PRODUCT RULE coverage** at this layer:
  - #1 (lunch and dinner only): no meal-type input on any auth
    surface; when `/verify` reads companion profile rows, `meal_types`
    is typed against `MealType` from `@/lib/types`.
  - #5 (one account, two modes): independent `is_seeker` /
    `is_companion` flags captured at sign-up and editable on `/mode`,
    with the at-least-one-mode invariant enforced at three layers
    (zod schema in sign-up action, the `updateUserModes` helper, and
    the `users_at_least_one_mode` CHECK constraint).
  - #9 (unverified companions are non-discoverable / non-bookable):
    as above.
  - #10 (card data never on our servers): no payment surface here;
    the only Storage writes are the profile photo + (private)
    verification document, both image-only, validated server-side.

- **Ran the gates that exist locally** (all green this run):
  - `npm run lint`       - clean.
  - `npm run type-check` - clean.
  - `npm run test`       - 50/50 unit tests pass across 5 files
    (`enums-transitions`, `profile-validators`, `parse-json-body`,
    `auth-gate`, `api-errors`).
  - `npm run build`      - 19 dynamic routes generated; auth surface
    confirmed (see route list above) and the auth-aware middleware
    is built at 87.2 kB.

- **No code changes** were required in this re-run. The artifact this
  invocation produces is the re-recorded orchestration log + the
  commit recording it.

WHAT I COULD NOT DO

- **End-to-end exercise the auth flow against a live Supabase
  project.** `.env.local` still ships placeholder Supabase URL / anon
  / service-role values (Foundations / founder territory), so no
  actual sign-up, login, password reset, OAuth callback, or Storage
  upload HTTP round-trip can be authorized today. Verification is
  currently typecheck + lint + unit tests + audit against the
  published schema + RLS policies. Same blocker the Database and Core
  API agents recorded.

- **Run the integration and RLS suites** (`tests/integration/*.test.ts`,
  `tests/rls/policies.test.ts`). The QA agent's harness `skipIf`s out
  without `TEST_SUPABASE_URL` / `TEST_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` /
  `TEST_SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`, which point at a disposable
  project (deliberately not dev). Operator-provisioned secrets - out
  of this agent's authority.

- **Promote a verified companion** end-to-end. The transition from
  `'pending'` to `'verified'` is intentionally not exposed in the
  application surface - it lives in the (yet-to-be-built) admin
  review surface. Flagged below.

- **Integrate an actual third-party identity check** (Stripe Identity
  / Persona / Veriff / equivalent). The Phase-1 flow captures legal
  name + an uploaded ID image into the private `verification` bucket
  and marks the row `'pending'`; the vendor-side review is the gap.
  Flagged below.

- **Deploy, push to git, modify secrets, or provision cloud
  infrastructure.** Operating rules - those are Foundations / the
  founder.

INTERFACES PUBLISHED

Frozen at the close of phase-1. Consumed by Frontend, Core API,
Payments, and Trust & Safety. All paths relative to the repo root.

- **Auth screens** (`app/(auth)/`):
  - `GET  /sign-up`               - email + password + display name +
    mode select + community guidelines acceptance (screen 1).
  - `GET  /login`                 - email + password.
  - `GET  /forgot-password`       - request password-reset email.
  - `GET  /reset-password`        - set a new password (callback-bound).
  - `GET  /check-email`           - landing after sign-up when email
    confirmation is required.
  - `GET  /mode`                  - one-account-two-modes switcher.
  - `GET  /verify`                - verification hub (seeker +
    companion, photo, guidelines, email).
  - `GET  /verify/companion`      - companion-only verification form
    (legal name + ID image upload).
  - `GET  /callback`              - Supabase Auth callback
    (`exchangeCodeForSession`).
  - `POST /verify/accept-guidelines` - records guidelines acceptance,
    reconciles seeker verification.
  - `POST /logout`                - clears the session cookie.

- **Server-side session helpers** (`@/lib/auth/session` -
  `server-only`):
  - `SessionUser` type: `{ id, email, emailConfirmed, profile }`.
  - `getSessionUser()` - returns the session user or `null`.
  - `requireSessionUser(redirectTo?)` - redirects to `/login` when
    signed out.
  - `requireMode(mode, redirectTo?)` - redirects to `/login` /
    `/verify` / `/mode` based on what's missing.

- **Server-side profile/mode helpers** (`@/lib/auth/profile` -
  `server-only`):
  - `createUserMirrorRow({ authUserId, email, displayName, isSeeker,
    isCompanion, acceptedGuidelines })` - idempotent upsert via the
    admin client; refuses to land a row with both mode flags false.
  - `updateUserModes({ isSeeker, isCompanion })` - request-scoped
    update; refuses to clear both flags.
  - `acceptGuidelines()` - stamps `users.guidelines_accepted_at`.

- **Server-side verification helpers** (`@/lib/auth/verification` -
  `server-only`):
  - `submitCompanionVerification({ legalName, documentPath })` -
    moves `companion_profiles.verification_status` from
    `'unverified'` to `'pending'`; idempotent for `'pending'` /
    `'verified'`.
  - `reconcileSeekerVerification(userId)` - syncs
    `users.seeker_verification_status` based on email-confirmed +
    guidelines-accepted.

- **Server-side storage helpers** (`@/lib/auth/storage` -
  `server-only`):
  - `AVATAR_BUCKET` / `VERIFICATION_BUCKET` constants.
  - `uploadAvatar(file: Blob)` - validates MIME + size, writes under
    `<userId>/avatar-<ts>.<ext>`, updates `users.avatar_path`.
  - `uploadVerificationDocument(file: Blob)` - same validation,
    writes under `<userId>/id-<ts>.<ext>` in the private bucket;
    non-upsert so the doc trail is preserved.
  - `avatarPublicUrl(avatarPath: string | null)` - resolves a public
    avatar URL for SSR rendering.

- **Client-side session context** (`@/lib/auth`):
  - `<AuthProvider initialSession={...}>` - wraps the app in
    `app/layout.tsx`; keeps the in-memory session in sync via
    Supabase's `onAuthStateChange`.
  - `useAuth()` - returns `{ session, isLoading, signOut }`. NOTE:
    client code that needs role / verification state must hit a
    server component or route handler - the auth-only session is not
    the authoritative source for `is_seeker` / `is_companion` /
    `verification_status`.

- **Storage convention** (frozen as the contract the Storage RLS
  migration `20260515010000_storage_rls.sql` is written against):
  - `avatars` bucket: public; writes restricted to
    `<auth.uid()>/avatar-*` keys; reads public.
  - `verification` bucket: private; reads + writes restricted to
    `<auth.uid()>/id-*` keys; no UPDATE (documents are write-once).

- **Session-cookie refresh contract** (`middleware.ts`):
  - Runs on every navigation / route except static assets + Next
    internals. Touches `getUser()` to force a cookie rewrite when the
    access token is near expiry. Falls through cleanly when the env
    is not configured yet.

MANUAL CHECKPOINTS

For the Orchestrator / Foundations / founder. None of these block
more Auth-agent code; they are the prerequisites for actually
exercising the flow end-to-end.

1. **Provision Supabase project envs** for `dev`, `staging`, `prod`.
   `.env.local` still ships placeholder `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL`,
   `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`, and `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`.
   Until those point at a real project no sign-up / login / Storage
   upload can be authorised.

2. **Configure Supabase Auth in the dashboard:**
   - Enable email + password sign-in.
   - Decide whether email confirmation is required (the flow handles
     both - returns to `/check-email` when no session is created, and
     to `/verify` when a session comes back immediately).
   - Set the Site URL and redirect allow-list to include
     `${NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL}/callback` for both confirmation and
     password-reset links.
   - Customise the confirmation / reset email templates so links
     resolve to `/callback?code=...&next=/reset-password` for the
     reset case.

3. **Apply the storage RLS migration** (`supabase/migrations/
   20260515010000_storage_rls.sql`) alongside the rest of the
   Database agent's contract. The `avatars` and `verification`
   buckets are also created at first upload by the Auth uploader as a
   fallback, but landing the migration ensures the policies are
   present on a fresh project before any user write.

4. **Wire the admin verification surface** so a `'pending'` companion
   can be moved to `'verified'` (or `'rejected'`). Out of phase-1
   scope and intentionally not exposed from the application surface.
   The minimum viable path is a service-role-backed admin route or a
   small Supabase Studio runbook; the production-grade path is an
   integrated third-party identity check (Stripe Identity / Persona /
   Veriff). Flag for Trust & Safety phase + Orchestrator routing of
   the vendor choice.

5. **Provision a disposable Supabase project for tests** with
   `TEST_SUPABASE_URL` / `TEST_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` /
   `TEST_SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`. Unblocks the QA agent's
   `tests/rls/policies.test.ts` (which verifies the unverified-
   companion fence on `companion_profiles`) and any future auth-flow
   integration tests.

6. **Open product decisions still routed to the founder via the
   Orchestrator** that touch this surface:
   - Identity-verification vendor choice (Stripe Identity / Persona
     / Veriff / etc.) - affects the companion verification flow.
   - Whether to require email confirmation before allowing seeker
     bookings - currently informational
     (`seeker_verification_status` is not used to gate the booking
     API; CORE PRODUCT RULE #9 only gates the companion side).
   - Whether the `display_name` on `users` should pass through a
     moderation / PII filter at sign-up (Trust & Safety).
   - Whether the community-guidelines copy is final - Trust & Safety
     owns the copy; we currently link to the (placeholder) page from
     the sign-up checkbox.
